  <br><br>
  <h4>I want them on my blog!</h4>
  <p>
    Good idea! You have three options. The first is the easiest but the other two work everywhere, not only Wordpress.
    <ul>
      <li><a href="#use-wordpress-plugin">1. Use our Wordpress plugin</a></li>
      <li><a href="#use-tldr-embed-code">2. Use the embed code in a tldr</a></li>
      <li><a href="#use-custom-code">3. Use a custom embed code</a></li>
    </ul>
  </p>

  <br>
  <div id="use-wordpress-plugin" class="anchor-before-h4-title"></div>
  <h4>1. Using the Wordpress plugin</h4>
  <p>
    We are still waiting for the plugin to be reviewed by the Wordpress.org plugin directory. In the meantime
    <strong><a target="_blank" href="https://www.dropbox.com/s/zul78qoloxop1x9/embed-wordpress-plugin.zip">you can download it</a></strong>
    and upload it to your Wordpress blog manually.
  </p>
  <p>
    With the tldr.io Wordpress plugin, you only need to put the custom shortcode <code>[tldrio_embed]</code> where you want the embedded summary of
    your post to be.
  </p>
  <img src="/assets/img/embed-screenshot-1.png" alt="Embedding the summary of your own article" class="img-rounded embed-screenshot">
  <p>
    You can also embed the summary of another article with the shortcode <code>[tldrio_embed someurl]</code> where <code>someurl</code> is the
    url of the article whose summary you want to embed. For example if you want the same embed as the one at the top of this page:
  </p>
  <img src="/assets/img/embed-screenshot-2.png" alt="Embedding the summary of any article" class="img-rounded embed-screenshot">
  <p>
    <strong><a target="_blank" href="https://www.dropbox.com/s/zul78qoloxop1x9/embed-wordpress-plugin.zip">Download it and make your blog awesome now!</a></strong>
  </p>

  <br>
  <div id="use-tldr-embed-code" class="anchor-before-h4-title"></div>
  <h4>2. Using the embed code in a tldr</h4>
  <p>
    If you don't have Wordpress, don't worry, this method and the next work everywhere. Wherever a tldr is displayed, you can easily get the HTML embed code.
    You can find it on the website and on the extension, and it's always at the same place: bottom right of the tldr:
  </p>
  <img src="/assets/img/embed-screenshot-4.png" alt="Embedding the summary of any article" class="img-rounded embed-screenshot">

  <br><br>
  <div id="use-custom-code" class="anchor-before-h4-title"></div>
  <h4>3. Using a custom code</h4>
  <p>
    Use this option for maximum flexibility or if you think the embed codes used in option #2 are too big. Here you need to use a small HTML code and choose
    the parameters you want to use with it.
  </p>
  <p>
    The code looks like this:<br>
    <code>
      &lt;blockquote OPTIONS_HERE class="tldr-embed-widget" style="display: none;"&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;<br>
      &lt;script async src="//tldr.io/embed/widget-embed.js" charset="utf-8"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
    </code>
  </p>
  <p>
    And the options:
    <ul>
      <li><code>data-use-own-tldr="true"</code> if you want to embed the summary of your own post</li>
      <li><code>data-url="some_url"</code> if you want to embed the summary an arbitrary url (if no tldr exists for the url the embed wil stay invisible)</li>
      <li><code>data-show-title="true|false"</code> if you want to show the title of the article in the embed (defaults to false)</li>
    </ul>
  </p>
  <p>
    For example, to show the same embed as the one at the top of the page, you need this code:<br>
    <code>
      &lt;blockquote data-url="http://paulgraham.com/hw.html" data-show-title="true" class="tldr-embed-widget" style="display: none;"&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;
      &lt;script async src="//tldr.io/embed/widget-embed.js" charset="utf-8"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
    </code>
  </p>

